What David really did

Not bravery alone. Not luck.

He changed the variables:
	•	Distance → turned close combat into ranged engagement
	•	Velocity → a sling can deliver lethal force fast, from outside reach
	•	Precision → target selection matters more than raw strength
	•	Mobility → light vs heavy

So the equation flips:

Giant optimized for contact dominance
David optimized for non-contact lethality

Different game.

⸻

“High ground wins” — but only if the game matches

High ground gives:
	•	visibility
	•	control of approach
	•	gravity advantage

But it’s just another assumption amplifier.

If the fight shifts—range, tools, terrain—
high ground can become irrelevant or even a trap.

⸻

The underdog advantage (when it exists)

Not guaranteed. But when it’s real, it usually comes from:
	•	Leverage mismatch
One side using a tool/strategy the other isn’t built to counter
	•	Game-switching
Refusing the obvious contest (strength vs strength)
	•	Lower expectation → higher freedom
The underdog isn’t bound by “how it’s supposed to be done”
	•	Overcommitment by the favorite
The stronger side invests too heavily in the wrong model

⸻

Clean way to see it

Don’t ask:

“Who is stronger?”

Ask:

“What game is actually being played… and who is optimized for that?”

Because the moment those two don’t match:

The “underdog” is often just
the only one playing the correct game.